A bit late to the party, but I recommend using a macro and a caller to do this!
```{% macro dynamic_tag(tag="div", attributes="" %}
  &lt;{{tag}} {{attributes}}&gt;
    {{caller()}}
  &lt;/{{tag}}&gt;
{% endmacro %}

// call the macro 
{% call dynamic_tag('h1', 'class="my-heading"' %}
  Hello world!
{% endcall %}

// renders as:
&lt;h1 class="my-heading"&gt;Hello world!&lt;/h1&gt;```
This pattern for dynamic tags comes with one big advantage: you can isolate the `dynamic_tag` macro in its own file and import it, which prevents the `&lt;{{tag}&gt;&lt;/{{tag}}&gt;` block from wreaking havoc on your syntax highlighting and indentation.
